  "title": "Circuit with two capacitors in equilibrium",
  "content": {
    "prompt": "<p><img alt=\"The figure shows a closed rectangular circuit diagram. On the left side there is a capacitor labeled C sub 1. On the right side there is a capacitor labeled C sub 2 equals 2 times C sub 1. On the top is an open switch labeled S.\" height=\"131\" src=\"/images/61db019e36b31f7282ff3171a6b8ee0f.jpg\" width=\"270\"></p>\n\n<p>A capacitor of capacitance <em>C</em><sub>1 </sub>is charged and then connected to another initially uncharged capacitor of capacitance<em> C</em><sub>2</sub> = 2<em>C</em><sub>1</sub>, as shown above, with the switch <em>S</em> in the open position. When <em>S</em> is closed and the system comes to equilibrium, which of the following is true of the charges on the capacitors and the potential differences across them?</p>\n",
    "answer": "i1",
    "choices": [
      {
